  <div class="relationship">
    <h3>Relationships</h3>
    <p><strong>Accounts:</strong> Each account belongs to a household member. Use the <code>household_member_id</code> foreign key to establish this relationship.</p>

    <p><strong>Transactions:</strong> Transactions are linked to both an account and a household member. Utilize the <code>account_id</code> and <code>household_member_id</code> foreign keys to connect transactions to their respective accounts and household members.</p>

    <p><strong>Transaction Categories:</strong> Transactions have multiple categories through the <code>TransactionCategories</code> table. Use the <code>transaction_id</code> and <code>category_id</code> foreign keys to establish a many-to-many relationship between transactions and categories.</p>

    <p><strong>Transaction Tags:</strong> Similar to categories, transactions can have multiple tags via the <code>TransactionTags</code> table. Use the <code>transaction_id</code> and <code>tag_id</code> foreign keys for a many-to-many relationship between transactions and tags.</p>

    <p><em>Note: Ensure proper ActiveRecord associations in your models for seamless navigation and data retrieval.</em></p>
